\begin_layout Abstract
\paragraph_spacing double
\noindent
A key question in macroeconomics is how aggregate consumption responds to
 a shock to gasoline expenditures.
 Using a structural VAR model for U.S.
 data covering the period 1973-2018, this paper shows that (i) an increase
 in gasoline expenditures reduces aggregate consumption, (ii) the response
 to a gasoline expenditures shock is much stronger in a recession than in
 an expansion, and (iii) the asymmetry in response over the business cycle
 is primarily due to differences in household savings behavior in recessions
 versus expansions.
 Our results are consistent with the literature showing larger effects of
 fiscal policy in recessions.
 
\end_layout

