\begin_layout Standard
An important question in macroeconomics is how aggregate consumption responds
 to a shock to gasoline expenditures.
 In one sense, the mechanism by which consumption is affected is straightforward.
 If gasoline consumption is inelastic in the short run, a positive shock
 to the price of gasoline will lead to higher gasoline expenditures, crowding
 out spending on other goods and services.
