\begin_layout Standard
The impulse responses of different measures of consumption to gasoline expenditu
re shocks in recessions and expansions are calculated using local projections.
 Local projections have the ability to accommodate non-linear specification
 (Jorda, 2005).
 The key advantage of using a nonlinear model instead of estimating a VAR
 for each regime is that with the latter we do not have enough observations
 to make a precise analysis.
 In our case, the observations for a recessionary regime only comprise 20%
 of the entire sample.
 As a result, our estimates of the VAR model for recessions would not have
 been precise due to insufficient observations.
 Estimating a non-linear model allows us to utilize the entire dataset for
 our inference.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that consumption expenditures respond contemporaneously to an increase
 in gasoline expenditures, the immediate response of consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 to a gasoline expenditure shock can be estimated with the following regression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{t}=\alpha+{\displaystyle {\displaystyle \sum_{i=0}^{k}\phi_{i}I_{t-i}+\sum_{i=0}^{k}\theta_{i}\triangle y_{t-i}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\beta_{i}c_{t-i}}+\sum_{i=0}^{k}\gamma_{i}\triangle gas_{t-i}+\sum_{i=0}^{k}\delta_{i}inter_{t-i}}+\varepsilon_{t}\label{eq:threshold}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
inter_{t-i}=I_{t-i}\times\triangle gas_{t-i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the percentage change in consumption in time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle gas_{t-i}$
\end_inset

 is the change in gasoline expenditures in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t-i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle y_{t-i}$
\end_inset

 is the GDP growth rate in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t-i$
\end_inset

.
 GDP growth rate and the recession dummy have been added to control for
 the state of the economy.
 
\begin_inset Formula $inter_{t-i}$
\end_inset

 represents the asymmetric response of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 when the economy is in a recession.
 Recession dates calculated using Auerbach and Gorodnichenko (2012) take
 the following value,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{t}=\begin{cases}
1 & F(z_{t})\geq0.8\\
0 & F(z_{t})<0.8
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the transition function that indicates the state of the economy and
 takes the following functional form,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(z_{t})=\frac{exp(-\gamma(z_{t}-\bar{d}))}{1+exp(-\gamma(z_{t}-\bar{d}))},\gamma>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the seven quarter moving average growth rate of output and
 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is calibrated to be equal to 3 so that the economy spends 20% of time in
 recession i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(F(z_{t})\geq0.8)=0.2$
\end_inset

 (Auerbach and Gorodnichenko, 2012).
 The value for the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{d}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 0.8.
 Recession dates are reconstructed using data available in the ‘lpirfs’
 package which was provided by Phillip Adammer.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Adämmer P (2019).
 lpirfs: Local Projections Impulse Response Functions.
 R package version: 0.1.5, https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=lpirfs.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Auerbach and Gorodnichenko (2012) sample period is 1947:Q1-2008:Q4.
 In order to identify periods of economic downturn for the sample period
 2009:Q1-2018:Q2, we rely on the NBER's recession dates provided by the
 FRED St.
 Louis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle gas_{0}$
\end_inset

 as the change in gasoline expenditure in recessions and expansions, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $inter_{0}$
\end_inset

 as the change in gasoline expenditures in recessions, the contemporaneous
 response of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}=\hat{\gamma}_{0}\triangle gas_{0}+\hat{\delta}_{0}inter_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the shock under study is a 10% increase in gasoline expenditures,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle gas_{0}=10\%$
\end_inset

.
 For a 10% shock in recessions, 
\begin_inset Formula $inter_{0}=10\%$
\end_inset

.
 For expansions, on the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $inter_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 After calculating the contemporaneous response, we define the response
 vector for each state of the economy.
 Response vector tells us the initial response of variables following a
 10% increase in gasoline expenditures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{i}^{rec}=\begin{bmatrix}c_{0} & \triangle gas_{0} & inter_{0}\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{i}^{exp}=\begin{bmatrix}c_{0} & \triangle gas_{0} & 0\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The s-period impulse responses are then calculated by estimating a reduced
 form regression,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{t}=\alpha+{\displaystyle {\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{k}\phi_{i}I_{t-i}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}\triangle y_{t-i}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\beta_{i}c_{t-i}}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\gamma_{i}\triangle gas_{t-i}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\delta_{i}inter_{t-i}}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

.5.
 The response for both regimes is calculated using the following,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{IR}_{s}^{rec}=\Phi_{s}d_{i}^{rec}=\hat{\beta}_{s}c_{0}+\hat{\gamma}_{s}\triangle gas_{0}+\hat{\delta}_{s}inter_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{IR}_{s}^{exp}=\Phi_{s}d_{i}^{exp}=\hat{\beta}_{s}c_{0}+\hat{\gamma}_{s}\triangle gas_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{s}=\begin{bmatrix}\hat{\beta}_{s} & \hat{\gamma}_{s} & \hat{\delta}_{s}\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we construct the impulse responses for both regimes, we can calculate
 the cumulative impulse response functions.
 The rationale to use cumulative impulse responses is that it allows us
 to calculate the deviation of consumption from its’ long-run level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CIR_{s}^{rec}=\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{rec}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CIR_{s}^{exp}=\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{exp}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1\ldots5.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to calculate the asymmetric response of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 to gasoline expenditure shocks, we take the difference between the impulse
 responses across recessions and expansions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CIR_{s}^{rec}-CIR_{s}^{exp}=\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{rec}-\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{exp}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\triangle CIR_{s}=\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{rec}-\sum_{j=0}^{s}\widehat{IR}_{j}^{exp}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle CIR_{s}<0$
\end_inset

, this means the response of consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 is stronger in a recession as compared to an expansion.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle CIR_{s}>0$
\end_inset

 suggests the opposite.
 We present impulse responses constructed at the 95% confidence interval.
 Standard errors are calculated using the Newey-West correction method because
 successive leading of the dependent variable induces serial correlation
 in the error term (Equiza-Goñi and Gracia, 2018; Ramey and Zubairy, 2018).
 The covariance matrices are calculated by estimating the full system of
 equations using seemingly unrelated regression model.
 That is being followed by pulling out relevant terms.
 If zero lies within the 95% confidence intervals, that suggests the difference
 in response is not statistically significant.
\end_layout

